  <!-- Main Content -->
  <main class="container my-5">
    <section id="history">
      <h2>The Journey of NTOG</h2>
      <p>
        The Nordic Thoracic Oncology Group (NTOG) was established in 1993 as a collaborative network of thoracic oncology specialists from Denmark, Finland, Iceland, Norway, and Sweden. Recognizing the need for a unified approach to tackle lung cancer—a leading cause of cancer-related mortality in the Nordic region—NTOG was formed to advance research, improve patient care, and foster professional collaboration across borders.
      </p>
      <h3>Early Years and Formation</h3>
      <p>
        In the early 1990s, thoracic oncology professionals from the Nordic countries began informal collaborations to share knowledge and resources. The success of these initial interactions highlighted the potential benefits of a formal network. Thus, NTOG was officially founded in 1993, providing a structured platform for joint clinical trials, research projects, and educational initiatives.
      </p>
      <h3>Milestones and Achievements</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>1995:</strong> Launched the first multicenter clinical trial on non-small cell lung cancer in the Nordic countries, enhancing treatment protocols and patient outcomes.</li>
        <li><strong>2000s:</strong> Expanded research into molecular genetics and personalized medicine, contributing to the global understanding of lung cancer biology.</li>
        <li><strong>2005:</strong> Hosted the inaugural Nordic Lung Cancer Symposium, fostering collaboration and knowledge exchange among clinicians and researchers.</li>
        <li><strong>2010s:</strong> Participated in international partnerships, aligning Nordic research efforts with global initiatives in thoracic oncology.</li>
        <li><strong>2015:</strong> Introduced educational programs and workshops aimed at training healthcare professionals in the latest diagnostic and treatment techniques.</li>
        <li><strong>2020:</strong> Adapted to virtual collaboration methods to continue research and communication during global challenges, ensuring ongoing progress in lung cancer care.</li>
      </ul>
      <h3>Ongoing Commitment</h3>
      <p>
        Throughout its history, NTOG has remained dedicated to:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Collaborative Research:</strong> Conducting joint clinical trials and studies to improve lung cancer diagnosis, treatment, and prevention.</li>
        <li><strong>Education:</strong> Providing training and resources for healthcare professionals to stay abreast of advancements in thoracic oncology.</li>
        <li><strong>Patient Advocacy:</strong> Supporting patient associations and advocating for policies that enhance patient care and access to treatments.</li>
        <li><strong>Innovation:</strong> Embracing new technologies and methodologies to advance research and improve patient outcomes.</li>
      </ul>
      <h3>Looking Forward</h3>
      <p>
        NTOG continues to build on its rich history, striving to make significant contributions to the field of thoracic oncology. By uniting experts across the Nordic countries, we aim to accelerate research discoveries, implement best practices in patient care, and ultimately reduce the burden of lung cancer in our region and beyond.
      </p>
      <p>
        We invite you to learn more about our work and join us in our mission to combat lung cancer through collaboration and innovation.
      </p>
      <a href="https://nordicthoraciconcologygroup.wordpress.com" class="btn btn-primary mt-3" target="_blank">Visit Our Previous Website</a>
    </section>
